## Hands-on Demo Commands (what we ran)

```bash
# 1. Install Flux on cluster
flux install

# 2. Create GitRepository (source-controller watches this)
flux create source git gitops-demo \
  --url=https://github.com/prabumohanur/gitops.demo.git \
  --branch=main \
  --interval=1m

# 3. Create HelmRelease (helm-controller deploys this)
flux create helmrelease demo-app-flux \
  --source=GitRepository/gitops-demo \
  --chart=./helm \
  --interval=1m \
  --target-namespace=default

# 4. Simulate PR merge — change values + bump version
# Edit helm/values.yaml: replicaCount: 1 → 2
# Edit helm/Chart.yaml:  version: 0.1.0 → 0.2.0
git add helm/values.yaml helm/Chart.yaml
git commit -m "feat: scale to 2 replicas"
git push origin main

# 5. Watch Flux sync
flux get helmreleases
kubectl get pods -n default
```

---

## One-liner Summary for Interview

> "FluxCD uses two resources — GitRepository tells source-controller to
> watch the GitHub repo, and HelmRelease tells helm-controller to deploy
> the chart. When a PR is merged with a bumped chart version, source-controller
> detects the new commit, creates an artifact, and helm-controller runs
> helm upgrade — bringing the new pods up in the target namespace."
